column19: As a part of our project, we would like to develop something that positively impacts people's day-to-day life. The idea we have selected in order to do this is an adjustable hanger that reduces the dexterity required in order to insert a hanger into clothes by virtue of its expandable capability. We would like to use this project as a means to apply concepts that we learn in class like tolerances/fits, material selection, and manufacturing process selection. It seems like our project will provide an interesting combination requiring all such considerations in order to achieve our goal of creating a functional and helpful product.

column22: We want to produce an adjustable hanger with auto-extending arms for clothes that have a smaller neck or those with limited dexterity.
column23: Our team wants to work on a product that simplifies daily tasks, such as dressing, that can also act as an assistive technology device. We aim to design, prototype, and test an adjustable hanger for a variety of clothes.
column24: Our goal with the hanger is to provide assistive technology to people with limited dexterity, particular, one-armed and senior individuals. The product can also be used by anyone to hang delicate clothes or clothes with small necks.
column25: Our goal is most likely to focus on the adjustable hanger to allow for easier hanging of clothes!

The idea we have selected in order to do this is an adjustable hanger that reduces the dexterity required in order to insert a hanger into clothes by virtue of its expandable capability. We would like to use this project as a means to apply concepts that we learn in class like tolerances/fits, material selection, and manufacturing process selection. It seems like our project will provide an interesting combination requiring all such considerations in order to achieve our goal of creating a functional and helpful product.
column21: Our team wants to design products that specifically aid people with mobility issues; our products may seem to be solving easy problems, but 1 in 4 people report having a disability (CDC). By creating products that can help with day to day life, we make everyone's lives easier while still giving those with disabilities autonomy to live on their own.
column22: We want to produce an adjustable hanger with auto-extending arms for clothes that have a smaller neck or those with limited dexterity.
column23: Our team wants to work on a product that simplifies daily tasks, such as dressing, that can also act as an assistive technology device. We aim to design, prototype, and test an adjustable hanger for a variety of clothes.
column24: Our goal with the hanger is to provide assistive technology to people with limited dexterity, particular, one-armed and senior individuals. The product can also be used by anyone to hang delicate clothes or clothes with small necks.
column25: Our goal is most likely to focus on the adjustable hanger to allow for easier hanging of clothes!

column19: Our team's goal is to complete assignments efficiently while learning from each other and developing skills in CAD, design, and prototyping. We focus on creating original ideas and improving through trial and error. However, we need to strengthen our collaboration, as it often feels like the priority is finishing assignments quickly rather than ensuring everyone fully understands the material. For example, during the installation of the Prusa driver for the "Making a 3D Printer Lab", important information wasn't shared with the entire group, limiting the learning experience. Similarly, instead of one person handling the CAD for the printer parts, it could have been a shared effort to ensure everyone gains confidence in designing for future group projects. If we overcome these challenges, our team will be much stronger and more enjoyable to work with.

However, we need to strengthen our collaboration, as it often feels like the priority is finishing assignments quickly rather than ensuring everyone fully understands the material. For example, during the installation of the Prusa driver for the "Making a 3D Printer Lab", important information wasn't shared with the entire group, limiting the learning experience. Similarly, instead of one person handling the CAD for the printer parts, it could have been a shared effort to ensure everyone gains confidence in designing for future group projects. If we overcome these challenges, our team will be much stronger and more enjoyable to work with.
column21: We want to be collaborative and learn from each other while hitting our deadlines and making continuous progress.
column22: Our team goal is to efficiently complete all of our assignments on time while learning from each others' perspectives. We want to all gain new skills from each other, the class, and machine shop while producing projects that are proficient and innovative. Inspire and guide each other through this semester, as we all bring different life experiences that are valuable to our Berkeley journey. We hope to learn from each other how to improve with CAD, how to move through a design process, and what trial-and-error looks like. Proficient and innovative means not necessarily taking an idea that already exists but instead coming up with our own, and building an acceptable prototype.
column23: We will accomplish this in a timely and meaningful fashion. We will stick to deadlines, be on time with CAD proficiency, on time with learning the design/manufacturing process, and on time with redoing via prototyping to create a successful working prototype. We will do this with our skill sets, teaching each other in a place of experience and compromising edits from design failure and prototype failure while supporting each other in our work.

column19: Our team, Breaking Cad, is still in the process of finalizing our project, but we remain committed to strong teamwork and effective communication.
